      <remark xml:id="rf-zeros-asymptotes-holes">
        <title>Features of a rational function</title>
       <p>
         Let <m>r(x) = \frac{p(x)}{q(x)}</m> be a rational function.
       </p>
  
       <p>
         <ul>
           <li>
             <p>
               If <m>p(a) = 0</m> and <m>q(a) \ne 0</m>, then <m>r(a) = 0</m>, so <m>r</m> has a <term>zero</term><idx><h>rational function</h><h>zero</h></idx> at <m>x = a</m>.
             </p>
           </li>
           <li>
             <p>
               If <m>q(a) = 0</m> and <m>p(a) \ne 0</m>, then <m>r(a)</m> is undefined and <m>r</m> has a <term>vertical asymptote</term><idx><h>rational function</h><h>vertical asymptote</h></idx> at <m>x = a</m>.
             </p>
           </li>
           <li>
             <p>
               If <m>p(a) = 0</m> and <m>q(a) = 0</m> and we can show that there is a finite number <m>L</m> such that
               <m>
                 r(x) \to L
               </m>,
               then <m>r(a)</m> is not defined and <m>r</m> has a <term>hole</term><idx><h>rational function</h><h>hole</h></idx> at the point <m>(a,L)</m>.
             </p>
           </li>
         </ul>
       </p>
      </remark>
    
